## What happened

**.NET 11 removed DSA support on macOS.** Apple dropped DSA from its security framework, and .NET 11 reflects that — `DSA.Create()` now throws on macOS. Windows and Linux are unaffected (DSA still works there, though it's considered legacy).

## How to fix it

Since you only **verify** legacy signatures, you have two options:

### Option 1 — Platform guard (keep DSA for Win/Linux)
```csharp
if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
    throw new PlatformNotSupportedException("DSA verification not supported on macOS in .NET 11+");

using var dsa = DSA.Create();
dsa.ImportParameters(legacyPublicKey);
bool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

### Option 2 — Migrate to ECDSA/RSA (recommended long-term)
```csharp
// Replace DSA with ECDSA for all platforms
using var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create();
var valid = ecdsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

This requires **re-signing** existing data with the new algorithm, so it's a larger effort — but it eliminates the legacy dependency entirely.

### Recommendation

If you **must** verify existing DSA signatures, use the platform guard (Option 1) and restrict DSA verification to Windows/Linux. For new signatures, move to **ECDSA** or **RSA**.
